  "aspect": "vertical", "theme": "navy", "fps": 30, "crossfade": 0.6, "pace": 1.4,
  "voiceover": "So who made God? It feels like it should stop the whole conversation — if everything needs a maker, then God needs one too, and it all collapses into an infinite regress. But it rests on a small misunderstanding of the claim. The argument from the universe's beginning never says everything has a cause. It says something narrower and more careful: whatever begins to exist has a cause. Things don't pop into being out of nothing. The universe, the evidence suggests, began to exist — so it needs a cause beyond itself. God, by definition, did not begin to exist. He's eternal. So he isn't an arbitrary exception; he simply falls outside a rule that was only ever about things that begin. Now, you can still ask good questions: is an eternal, uncaused being coherent? Could the universe itself be eternal? Ask them. But 'who made God' is a bit like asking what the bachelor's wife is doing tonight — it presupposes what the claim already ruled out. Whatever is the ultimate explanation of everything must, by its nature, be something that never needed to be made.",
  "source": "answers/who-made-god.html",
  "scenes": [
